diff:1618108665:1618108665:=1,91d0%0a%3c (:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c [[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a%3c [[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c [[!MorphosyntacticDiversity]]%0a%3c %0a%3c !Linguistics is so cool anymore%0a%3c %0a%3c :Author: ruiranx%0a%3c %0a%3c '''Summary:''' \\%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summary]]%0a%3c %0a%3c An examination of the word "anymore" used in a non-negative context%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summaryends]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c In standard English, the word "anymore" is known as a negative polarity item (NPI), which means it appears in negative contexts. For example, consider the sentences "I don't even know anymore" and "this doesn't make sense anymore".%0a%3c %0a%3c However, across the United States, "anymore" can be used in a positive context so that its meaning is similar to the word "nowadays". For example, consider the following examples[1].%0a%3c %0a%3c - Anymore, John smokes.%0a%3c - You stay in your office too late anymore.%0a%3c %0a%3c These would both make sense in the context of standard English when "anymore" is substituted with "nowadays".%0a%3c %0a%3c - Nowadays, John smokes.%0a%3c - You stay in your office too late nowadays.%0a%3c %0a%3c It's worth noting that this positive kind of "anymore" can only be used in present tense, precisely because its meaning is analogous to "nowadays". To highlight this point, consider the following variants on the second example from before.%0a%3c %0a%3c - You stayed in your office too late anymore.%0a%3c - You stayed in your office too late nowadays.%0a%3c %0a%3c - You will stay in your office too late anymore.%0a%3c - You will stay in your office too late nowadays.%0a%3c %0a%3c Linguists assert that usage of the positive "anymore" is fairly scattered, but also somewhat clustered in the Midwest[2]. Furthermore, research suggests that this construct is of Scots-Irish origin [3].%0a%3c %0a%3c [1] https://ygdp.yale.edu/phenomena/positive-anymore%0a%3c [2] https://schwa.byu.edu/files/2014/11/F2013-Reynolds.pdf%0a%3c [3] https://twpl.library.utoronto.ca/index.php/twpl/article/download/6249/3237/%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Comments%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (:section: F:)%0a%3c (:Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
